Archives and compression — tar and the tar-pipe.

Two ideas that people constantly blur together, so let's keep them separate. Archiving means bundling many files into one stream. On Linux that job belongs to tar, whose name comes from "tape archive." Compressing means making a stream smaller, and there are several algorithms to choose from depending on the trade-off you want. tar archives; a compressor shrinks. They're different steps that just happen to be used together.

tar has three operations you'll actually use, and they map to three letters. tar dash-c-z-f, with a name and a directory, creates a gzipped archive: c for create, z for gzip, f for file. tar dash-x-z-f extracts one: x for extract. And tar dash-t-z-f lists the contents, so you can peek inside without unpacking. A nice detail: the compression letter picks the algorithm, dash-z for gzip, dash-j for bzip2, capital dash-J for xz, and dash-dash-zstd for zstd, but on extraction you can leave it out entirely. Modern tar autodetects the compression when unpacking, so tar dash-x-f just works. You only specify the algorithm when creating.

Which algorithm should you pick? For exam-level work, really know two. gzip is fast, universally supported, and the safe default for almost everything. xz is slow to compress but gives an excellent ratio, so it's what you see for distribution packages and long-term archival. And keep an eye on zstd: it's very fast in both directions with a very good ratio, and it's quietly becoming the modern default, it's already used in the systemd journal, in Btrfs compression, and across recent distributions.

Finally, a lovely trick: the tar-pipe. When you give tar dash-f and then just a single dash, it reads from or writes to standard input or output instead of a file. That means you can pipe one tar straight into another and copy an entire directory tree without ever creating an archive file on disk. tar dash-c-f dash on the source, piped into tar dash-x-f dash dash-capital-C into the destination. The classic use is over SSH, which is module eight: compress on one side, stream across the network, decompress on the other, with no intermediate file. For routine machine-to-machine copies you'd usually prefer rsync, also module eight, because it only transfers what changed. But the tar-pipe works on the barest system imaginable. The takeaway to remember: dash-f dash means "use standard in and standard out," and that's what makes tar composable with the rest of your pipeline.
